---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import TreeWorld from '../components/TreeWorld.astro';
---

<Base active="home">
  <!-- ───────────────────────── hero ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="hero section">
    <div class="wrap hero__copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">An experiment in building software with AI agents</p>
      <h1>Software you can watch grow.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Building with AI&nbsp;agents is fast — and a blur. The code writes itself; the hard part is
        <em>seeing</em> what it built, trusting it, and keeping humans and agents pointed the same way.
        storytree turns a project into a living map you — and your agents — can read at a glance: what
        exists, what's proven, what's broken. Nothing goes green until a failing check is made to pass.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/how-it-works/">See how it works →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/constitution/">Read the constitution</a>
      </div>
      <p class="hero__note muted">
        Small on purpose. Invite-only for now — but the door to ask is wide open.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── the live map, front and centre ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="demo-lead">
        Here's a whole system in storytree's map view — a made-up team-chat backend. Bigger trees have
        more behind them; red is where a check is failing. <strong>Hover or tap a tree</strong> to
        inspect a story, or click to pin it and light up everything it depends on.
      </p>
      <TreeWorld />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── the idea ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="lede">
        Picture your whole system as a place you can walk — not a wall of diffs and a chat log that
        scrolls forever, but a living map of <strong>stories</strong>, where colour is health and you
        can see at a glance what your agents actually built. That's the shape of storytree: a project
        grows as a map you can read, and the work stays out in the open where it can be checked.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── three pillars ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="grid grid--3">
        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <circle cx="13" cy="17" r="4.5" fill="#2f6b3f"/>
              <circle cx="27" cy="14" r="4.5" fill="#55a06a"/>
              <circle cx="22" cy="27" r="4.5" fill="#b06a24"/>
              <path d="M13 17 L27 14 M13 17 L22 27" stroke="#a98e5f" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>A swarm of agents, one map</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            People and AI&nbsp;agents build in parallel, fast. Instead of a separate chat log to
            re-read per agent, one shared map shows who's touching what, where the proof stands, and
            what's still just an idea.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <path d="M12 20.5 l5 5 l11 -12" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="3.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Nothing ships without proof</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            A green node isn't the model's say-so. It's a check that was <em>failing</em>, made to
            pass for the right reason, with a human sign-off. Agents reward-hack; a failing check made
            to pass is harder to fake. "Done" means evidence, not vibes.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="card pillar">
          <div class="pillar__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40">
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="17" fill="var(--evergreen-soft)"/>
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="9" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="2.6"/>
              <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="2.6" fill="#b06a24"/>
              <path d="M20 4 V9 M20 31 V36 M4 20 H9 M31 20 H36" stroke="#2f6b3f" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3>You don't have to trust us</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            The decisions, the reasoning, and the record are open and meant to be checked. We're
            building toward a way to simply <em>ask</em> the project, against its whole record — so a
            hidden agenda has nowhere left to hide.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── the bet ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap band">
      <div class="band__inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">The bet</p>
        <h2>An open record is a stronger foundation for trust than promises.</h2>
        <p class="lede">
          Most projects ask you to trust the people running them. We're trying to show you don't have
          to. When agents write most of the code and humans can't read all of it, the thing that keeps
          a project honest isn't good intentions — it's a complete, open record you can interrogate
          directly. If that works, it's a fairer way to build software, and one more people can take
          part in. If it doesn't, you'll be able to see that too.
        </p>
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/how-it-works/">How the pieces fit together →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ───────────────────────── front door ───────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose front">
      <p class="eyebrow">Where we are right now</p>
      <h2>Early, honest, and growing slowly.</h2>
      <p>
        storytree isn't open source yet — it's not ready to be. Taking part is invite-only while we
        iterate out the rough edges and build the guardrails real openness needs. Today one person
        still decides what gets built next — we're honest that "your voice counts" isn't yet "your
        vote counts." But this website is the open front door: you're welcome to watch, to ask hard
        questions, and to tell us where we're wrong — that last one especially.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/contact/">Ask to come in</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/how-it-works/">Just looking? Start here</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero { padding-top: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.4rem); padding-bottom: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 2.2rem); }
  .hero__copy { max-width: 50rem; }
  .hero__copy h1 { margin-top: 0.2rem; }
  .demo-lead { max-width: 44rem; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 1.02rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
  .demo-lead strong { color: var(--ink); }
  .hero__cta { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.7rem; margin-top: 1.6rem; }
  .hero__note { margin-top: 1.3rem; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .hero em { font-style: italic; color: var(--ink); }

  .pillar { display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .pillar__icon { margin-bottom: 0.7rem; }
  .pillar h3 { margin-bottom: 0.35rem; }
  .pillar p { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .pillar em { font-style: italic; }

  .band {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #2f6b3f 0%, #245031 100%);
    border-radius: calc(var(--radius) + 4px);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    overflow: hidden;
    position: relative;
  }
  .band::after {
    content: ""; position: absolute; inset: 0;
    background:
      radial-gradient(420px 300px at 92% -20%, rgba(169,200,127,0.30), transparent 60%),
      radial-gradient(360px 260px at 0% 120%, rgba(214,178,113,0.22), transparent 60%);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .band__inner { position: relative; padding: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.4rem); max-width: 46rem; }
  .band .eyebrow { color: #f2cd92; }
  .band h2, .band .lede { color: #fdf6ec; }
  .band .lede { color: #e7ecdf; }
  .band h2 { margin-bottom: 0.7rem; }
  .band .btn--primary { background: #fffdfa; color: var(--evergreen-deep); margin-top: 0.4rem; }
  .band .btn--primary:hover { background: #fff; color: var(--evergreen-deep); }

  .front h2 { margin-top: 0.2rem; }
</style>
